> Dear Fellow Theoretical Chemists:
>
> I am pleased to announce two Summer Schools to be held here at Virginia
> Tech this year that may be of interest to you or your colleagues.
>
> *Third Annual Software Summer School, June 22-July 1:
> <http://s2i2.org/school_2015/index.html>*  This NSF-sponsored Summer
> School targets first- and second-year graduate students whose Ph.D.
> research requires significant programming skills.  The School, which is
> part of the sustainable software initiative led by the SICM2 Project, wil=
l
> cover a range of software design and optimization, including programming
> fundamentals, numerical libraries, parallel computing, and GPU/accelerato=
r
> algorithms.
>
> http://s2i2.org/school_2015/
>
> Interested students should submit an application consisting of a CV,
> letter of support, and a brief description of their research and how it
> would benefit from the advanced programming skills offered by the School.
> Students accepted to the program will need only provide their own
> transportation to the Virginia Tech campus; *all other expenses,
> including room, board, and instructional costs will be covered by the
> School*.  (Note that only student at U.S. institutions are eligible for
> participation in this year's Software Summer School.)
>
> ----------------------
>
> *Molecular Response Properties Summer School, June 29-July 3:
> <http://www.theory.chem.vt.edu/response/index.html>*  Much of our
> understanding of molecules and materials is derived from their responses =
to
> electromagnetic fields =E2=80=93 from high-resolution spectroscopic analy=
ses for
> the identification of molecules in interstellar space, to magnetic
> resonance imaging used in medical diagnostics, to non-linear fiber optics
> employed in telecommunications. This school will focus on the quantum
> mechanical theories underlying both weak- and strong-field responses, in
> absorption, emission, and scattering, at a level appropriate for graduate
> students and postdoctoral researchers.
>
> http://www.theory.chem.vt.edu/response/
>
> The School will be taught by Profs. Patrick Norman (Link=C3=B6ping U., Sw=
eden),
> Trond Saue (U. Toulouse), Kenneth Ruud (Arctic University of Norway), and
> Daniel Crawford (Virginia Tech).   Interested participants may register a=
t
> the above website (no application process is otherwise required).  *The
> $550 registration fee includes room, board, and instructional expenses, b=
ut
> not transportation costs.*
